snippet.textDisplay:
I just want to let the MtG team, and the folks who animated this, know they did a good job and made a fun and engaging trailer. Personally I loved the goofy approach (Shrek vibes and all, I thought it was fitting). If I could add one wish, I would have liked to have seen more hand to hand action, but I realize that would have taken longer to animate.

Please don't take the complaints of a vocal minority too seriously; there will always be people uncomfortable with change, who don't want to share "their" hobby with new audiences, who feel entitled to have creative direction suit their preferences. Keep coming up with cool trailer ideas and help us share the game we love with new folks.

Thanks guys!
snippet.textOriginal:

Personally I loved the goofy approach (Shrek vibes and all, I thought it was fitting). Please don't take the complaints of a vocal minority too seriously; there will always be people uncomfortable with change, who don't want to share "their" hobby with new audiences, who feel entitled to have creative direction suit their preferences. Keep coming up with cool trailer ideas and help us share the game we love with new folks.

Thanks guys!

snippet.textDisplay: The visuals are great but I honestly enjoyed the older trailers that showed the cards in stop motion animations in the set and it always felt like anything can happen when you have a planeswalker involved with the set and narrate their perspectives. It was enticing, it was interesting, and it was also grand to see what are we gonna do and see in this new set with the lore. And despite War of the Spark book - which I'll keep my opinions to myself - the trailer was visually beautiful and definitely entering new zones in animation. And even if they didn't say a single word in that trailer the music was nice. Even if it was odd to hear a mainstream song in the MTG brand. It may just be me but it did feel like they were trying a little too hard to pose for a bigger audience. Then This trailer... and it did what W.O.T.S. did but... in an awkward scale. It simply doesn't reach my interest, I know of Vivien and her personality but the trailer just felt like it was trying too hard to be a joke and the music didn't flow. I mean take skull island for example, the humans were definitely not at the top of the food chain and they showed just how terrifying it is to be met with creatures bigger and tougher than humans. All in all the trailer doesn't look bad at all, but in the end (no pun intended) i didn't feel like it was an MTG trailer. It didn't tell me anything other than big monsters and if they were trying tell us that humans were not gonna survive this plane so easily, then they shouldn't have shown us that all you need is one human (albeit a planeswalker) who has no trouble taking down the big monsters with her own big monsters. It robs us of the chance to see how dire the situation is. It doesn't show that she struggles with the beast. I mean in one old trailer Gideon almost died to Bolas when he was alone, a man known for being indestructible and he called out to his allies that sent a message: strength in numbers is the key in that trailer. Now I know that he was fighting another planeswalker who was bigger and stronger but planeswalkers could be killed by anything and the example was in relation to the context, small human vs big creature. I'm not saying that I hate the trailer but it just doesn't feel like MTG to me with them adding another highly recognized song to draw more audiences with no enticing trailer like how they used to. I don't hate the music they chose just how they chose to go about the trailer. I'm a strong believer that change is good but never forget the roots you grew from.
